turns.patient: I don't know why I'm here. My wife made me come. Everything's fine, I guess.
turns.therapist: You keep saying "fine". Tell me more about that.

turns.patient: *shrugs* I mean, what else am I supposed to say? "Fine" works - it gets people off my back and we can all move on with our lives. *fidgets with sleeve* Though I guess if "fine" was actually fine, I probably wouldn't be sitting in this chair, would I?
turns.therapist: "Fine" doesn't sound fine. You're here, and "fine" got you a seat in this chair.

turns.patient: *lets out a dry laugh* Well, aren't you perceptive. *shifts in chair* Look, my sister made me come here after I... had a bit of a meltdown at Thanksgiving dinner. Apparently throwing mashed potatoes and storming out isn't "fine" behavior. *rolls eyes* Who knew?
turns.therapist: That meltdown was more than just about the dinner. The anger's still right there under the surface.

turns.patient: *jaw tightens slightly* Yeah, well, maybe it is. *looks away* But it's not like I woke up that morning planning to redecorate the dining room with side dishes. *voice gets quieter* Everyone was just sitting there, pretending everything was perfect, and I... I couldn't do it anymore.
turns.therapist: The perfection facade cracked that morning. What were you really smashing with those side dishes?

turns.patient: *stares at the floor for a moment* I don't know... everything? *voice wavers slightly* The way my mom kept asking when I was going to "figure my life out," my dad ignoring me like usual, everyone acting like we're this happy family when we all know it's bullshit. *clenches fists* I guess I was smashing the whole damn lie.
turns.therapist: The anger is directed at your family, but the words are about something more specific. Tell me about the "lie" you were smashing.
